**Description:** Aywin Deepwater is a Drow, driven by an obsession with divine magic. Born as a high elf, Aywin was drawn to the call of Lolth, and was changed into something more dark, and twisted: a Drow. Despite the new abilities brought about by the darkness, Aywin's desire for divine knowledge lead him to wanting more than the Queen of Spiders herself could offer. 

Risking his new deity's wrath, he sought more, leading him to the Astral plane, where he encountered Hecate, the goddess of magic and moons. Aywin spent 62 years displaced from time, studying all forms of magic and language. Emerging from the plane, Aywin found that his desire for knowledge had not yet been quenched, and he now searches for Loki, the trickster god.

Aywin has been almost completely consumed with this quest for knowledge. His name Deepwater comes from his former life as a pirate, but it is a life he has all but forgotten.

------

+++++ **Gameplay:**

3 Artificer levels (Pick Armorer at level 3), 2 Levels of Warlock: Genie (take Mask of Many Faces and Grasp of Hadar for your invocations), then at least 7 more levels in artificer for the magic item crafting. 

The general goal is to multiclass 1 level into Warlock-Genie for the Bottled Respite, and then using Indefinite/Ritual spells to create a sort of sanctuary inside of the vessel. Early on, you can use magical tinkering to create lights, smells, sounds, and pictures to create a customizable relaxing space.

Starting off use the handaxe as your primary, and look for any melee/ranged weapons on your adventures you can find. The most ideal standard weapon is a trident. At Artificer level 3, you can infuse your weapon with Returning Weapon, and at Warlock level 3, you can turn this infused weapon into your pact weapon. This gives you a melee/ranged combo weapon weapon with +1 that will always return to your hand after your throw it, that you can keep in a pocket dimension and recall at will.

Once you get to the 9th Warlock level, you can learn Glyph of Warding. Glyphs of warding can be used to set spells like mage armor to trigger immediately upon entering the vessel, and glyphs used on objects inside the vessel can allow you to "store" healing and buff spells that you can use later without expending a spell slot. 

Spells like Private Sanctum can be used to add additional protection to the interior of the vessel, especially in long (story wise) campaigns where you can cast it every day to make the effect permanent. I typically will use sanctum to create a cube covering 90% of the extra-dimensional interior, and creating a 5 foot area where creatures will be forced to stand when entering the vessel. This means if you pull an enemy into the vessel during combat, they will be forced into the small area not blocked by the sanctum, where you can easily set traps that they will be forced to walk on. 

Leomund's Secret Chest can be used to store the vessel in a safe space, preventing it from being broken, or its glyphs being triggered early. Create Homunculus can be used within the vessel to have a permanent servant within your vessel. Because Aywin is a Drow, he can immediately use the vessel to trance as soon as he multiclasses.

+++++ Homunculus
Obviously, you can customize the Artificer Homunculus however you want, but this is the one designed for Aywin:

100 gp gem (preferably amethyst) for the heart. Aywin carries with him a specialized machination of his own design known as an Archimedes Sphere[[footnote]]this concept is heavily inspired by the Archimedes Sphere's from the Percy Jackson universe, mixed with a spellbook that the Runesmith (Logan) came up with in an arcane arcade campagin that ill find and link here eventually instead of this rambling sentence.[[/footnote]]. The sphere is about twice the size of a baseball, and is made up of smooth plates made out of varying metals that fit perfectly together. Inset within the sphere are 10 holes, 5 on each side, which Aywin can place his fingers into, to activate the sphere. When activate, the panels and dials of the sphere expand outward and twist and rotate, almost like a jedi holocron. By manipulating the device through the controls, Aywin can read or transcribe messages through a unique blend of clicks and whirs that almost resemble morse code, and cannot be heard from outside the device. This effectively allows for Aywin to have an impossible to crack diary that can store a theoretical infinite amount of information. 

At the center of this device sits a chamber for a crystal. Upon reaching Artificer level 2, and after acquiring a 100 gp gem (preferably an amethyst), Aywin can turn this device into a sentient automaton through the Homunculus Infusion. Doing so will allow the sphere to fully transform, usually into some sort of sphere with legs, resembling a large bug. The homunculus behaves just like the regular infusion based homunculus, but it also doubles as a notebook/diary. It's up to the DM whether the method of writing to the device allows you to communicate with the homunculus silently.

Aywin originally designed this device to be a Wizard's grimoire as he had aspirations to become a wizard, but his time in the astral plane has changed him, and he has long forgotten that dream. If  you do end up multiclassing Aywin into Wizard, or if he aquires any sort of book or grimoire, he would more than likely record it in his Archimedes Sphere.



